%N A387913 Hodge number h^{1,n-1} of a smooth hypersurface of degree n+2 in P^{n+1}.
%C A387913 This is the Hodge number h^{1, n-1} of a smooth hypersurface of degree n+2 in P^{n+1}, except for n=2 where the full Hodge number is 20. In this special case only, the Hodge number h^{1, n-1} sits at the center of the Hodge diamond, which explains the difference of 1.
%H A387913 G. Bini and A. Garbagnati, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.geomphys.2013.10.001">Quotients of the Dwork pencil</a>, Journal of Geometry and Physics, 75 (2014), 173-198. Cf. Remark 2.3.
%F A387913 a(n) = binomial(2*n+3,n+2)-(n+2)^2.
%F A387913 From _Stefano Spezia_, Sep 12 2025: (Start)
%F A387913 G.f.: 1 + (1/sqrt(1 - 4*x) - 1 - 2*x)/(2*x^2) - (4 - 3*x + x^2)/(1 - x)^3.
%F A387913 E.g.f.: 1 - exp(x)*(4 + 5*x + x^2) + exp(2*x)*(4*x*BesselI(0, 2*x) - BesselI(1, 2*x) + 4*x*BesselI(1, 2*x))/x. (End)
%e A387913 For n=1, an elliptic curve has Hodge number h^{1,0}=1. For n=2, a K3 surface has Hodge number h^{1,1}=20=19+1. For n=3, a smooth quintic threefold has Hodge number h^{1,2}=101.
